<h2>What "Check Stub" Means and Who Uses This Term</h2>
<p>The term "check stub" belongs to a different era of American payroll. When every worker received a paper check on payday, the check came attached to a document showing the earnings breakdown. You tore the check off along the perforated line and cashed it. The piece that remained -- the stub -- documented what the check represented. That document was called a check stub.</p>

<p>The people who still use this term tend to be in industries where paper checks remain common: construction, trucking, agriculture, manufacturing, and some trades. Workers in these industries often still receive physical checks on Fridays, cash them at the bank or a check cashing service, and keep the stub as their record. When they need income documentation for an apartment application or a loan, they reach for the phrase they have always used: "check stub."</p>

<p>The document you need is identical to what the rest of the world calls a pay stub or paycheck stub. Same format, same information, same purpose. This tool generates it.</p>

<h2>Industries Where Check Stubs Are Still the Standard</h2>

<h3>Construction and contracting</h3>
<p>Construction is one of the last industries with widespread paper check usage. Many general contractors and subcontractors pay workers weekly by check. The amount can vary based on hours worked, materials handled, weather days lost, and whether overtime applied. Formal payroll software is less common at smaller construction firms, and many workers receive checks directly from a job foreman or site supervisor. Check stubs for construction workers may need to account for regular pay, overtime, and sometimes per diem allowances.</p>

<h3>Trucking and freight</h3>
<p>Owner-operators and long-haul truckers often receive settlement checks rather than regular paychecks. A settlement check from a carrier covers the load revenue minus fuel surcharges, dispatch fees, insurance deductions, and other carrier expenses. The stub for a trucking settlement can look different from a standard paycheck stub -- it may include per-mile rates, loaded miles, and various deductions. For documentation purposes, a standard check stub format showing gross pay and net pay is typically what landlords and lenders need.</p>

<h3>Agriculture and seasonal work</h3>
<p>Farm workers, orchard workers, and other agricultural employees are often paid by the hour or by piece rate (bushels picked, rows weeded) by week or per harvest period. Many agricultural employers still use paper checks, and formal payroll systems may not exist at smaller operations. Workers who have been paid in cash or by check without formal stubs need check stub documentation when they seek housing or apply for benefits.</p>

<h3>Small retail and service businesses</h3>
<p>A small restaurant, a family-owned store, or a local service company with three to eight employees may still cut checks manually rather than using payroll software. The owner or bookkeeper writes the check; there is no payroll software generating a formatted stub. Creating check stubs for these employees provides them with the documentation they need for their personal financial transactions.</p>

<h3>Day labor and per-job work</h3>
<p>Some workers are paid per job or per day rather than on a recurring payroll schedule. A handyman paid $200 for a weekend project, a landscaper paid per visit, or a cleaner paid per home they clean may receive cash or checks with no accompanying documentation. Check stubs covering those payments provide the income documentation these workers need.</p>

<h2>The Shift Away from Paper Checks and Why Check Stubs Still Matter</h2>
<p>Direct deposit now covers the majority of American payroll transactions. Large employers have moved almost entirely to electronic payments. The check as a form of payroll disbursement is declining each year. But the check stub -- the documentation record -- has not declined. If anything, the decoupling of payment from documentation has made proper stub documentation more important, not less.</p>

<p>When you received a paper check with a stub attached, you automatically had documentation every payday. With direct deposit, the money arrives but you only have documentation if you actively access your HR portal or payroll system and download it. Workers who do not use these systems -- or workers whose employers do not provide them -- end up with bank statements but no formatted income documentation.</p>

<p>Check cashing businesses, which serve a significant portion of workers in cash-intensive industries, do not generate check stubs either. If you cash a paper check at a check casher rather than depositing it, your bank does not have a record. A check stub creator lets you document those earnings regardless of how you chose to receive the funds.</p>

<h2>What Goes on a Check Stub</h2>
<p>A properly formatted check stub includes all of the following:</p>

<p><strong>Employer information:</strong> Business name, address, and employer identification number (EIN) if you have it. For small informal employers, the business name and address is sufficient.</p>

<p><strong>Employee information:</strong> Your name, address, and optionally your Social Security number (last four digits only is common) or employee ID.</p>

<p><strong>Pay period:</strong> The date range this check covers, such as November 4-10 or the week of November 7.</p>

<p><strong>Check date:</strong> The date on the check itself.</p>

<p><strong>Earnings:</strong> Regular hours and rate (or flat pay), plus any overtime, piece rate, or other additional pay types.</p>

<p><strong>Gross pay:</strong> Total earnings before any deductions.</p>

<p><strong>Deductions:</strong> Federal income tax withheld, Social Security (6.2%), Medicare (1.45%), state income tax, and any other deductions like garnishments or union dues.</p>

<p><strong>Net pay:</strong> The amount of the check -- what you actually received.</p>

<p><strong>Year-to-date totals:</strong> Running totals of gross pay, each deduction, and net pay since January 1 of the current year.</p>

<h2>Check Stubs and Loan Applications</h2>
<p>Workers in cash-intensive industries often find that their loan applications require more documentation than workers in formal employment situations. A bank extending a personal loan, an auto lender, or a mortgage company all want to see documented, consistent income. Check stubs -- whether generated or issued by an employer -- provide that documentation.</p>

<p>For auto loans in particular, dealers and financing companies are accustomed to working with self-employed and informal workers. Bringing a set of check stubs covering the past three months, along with bank statements showing consistent deposits, is often sufficient for a car loan approval even when the income comes from informal or variable sources.</p>

<p>Personal loans through banks and credit unions are similarly workable with check stub documentation. Online lenders like LightStream and SoFi may accept bank statements alone, which provides an alternative if check stubs are not your primary documentation type. See our <a href="/pay-stub-for-loan">pay stub for loan applications</a> guide for specifics by lender type.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<h3>Is a check stub the same as a pay stub?</h3>
<p>Yes. "Check stub" is the older term, common in blue-collar industries where paper checks are still used. "Pay stub" is the more modern, widely used term. Same document, same format, same purpose.</p>

<h3>What if my employer doesn't give me check stubs?</h3>
<p>Some small employers, particularly in construction and agriculture, pay by check without generating formal stubs. You can create stubs yourself based on your actual earnings. These document your real income even when your employer does not provide formal documentation.</p>

<h3>Can I make a check stub for cash payments?</h3>
<p>Yes. If you are paid in cash, you can create check stubs documenting those cash payments. The documentation is only useful for verification if your actual bank deposits or other records support the income you're documenting -- cash stubs with no corresponding bank activity are difficult to verify and may raise questions with careful reviewers.</p>

<h3>What about truckers paid by settlement?</h3>
<p>Trucking settlements include various carrier deductions that do not appear on a standard check stub. For documentation purposes, most landlords and lenders just need to see gross pay and net pay for recent periods. You can simplify by entering your net settlement amount as the base pay figure for stub creation.</p>

<h3>Do I need my employer's EIN?</h3>
<p>For documentation purposes, the employer's EIN is not always required. Business name and address are usually sufficient. If your employer is a sole proprietor paying you informally, use their name and address. If you do have the EIN, including it adds credibility.</p>

<h3>How many check stubs do I need for a loan?</h3>
<p>Most lenders want two to three months of recent stubs. For a weekly pay schedule, that means eight to twelve stubs. For biweekly, four to six stubs. Generate enough to cover the most recent 60 to 90 days.</p>

<h3>Can construction workers with variable hours use this?</h3>
<p>Yes. Enter the actual hours and rate for each period. Construction hours vary by week depending on weather, project phase, and available work. Realistic variation in the stubs -- some weeks with 40 hours, some with 35 or 48 -- is appropriate and expected for construction documentation.</p>

